I think he just meant that:
    void foo(std::vector<char const* > &vec2)
    {
        ...
    }<p><pre><code>    ...

    std::vector<char*> vec1(...);
    foo(vec1); // fails
    </code></pre>
The idea is that you should be allowed to pass non-const vector to const function who accepts same vector (const or not const) with const variables. Because the function <i>foo</i> is like saying &quot;give me vector, I will not modify it&#x27;s elements&quot;, and with current C++ standard this is not allowed.
